{"key":"post-11663000","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>11663000</id>\n<content>Previous advice givers over the years to use a long-term buffer in casing layers neglect to realize one thing: A casing layer is a &lt;i&gt;short term&lt;/i&gt; item.&amp;nbsp; A casing layer is rarely in service two months later, and while long term buffers such as ground limestone(calcium carbonate) are fine, they're not required.&amp;nbsp; Using hydrated lime alone works great.&amp;nbsp; Start with about 1 teaspoon of hydrated lime per cup of peat moss.&amp;nbsp; Give it an hour or two to stabilize and add more if necessary to get the pH to about 8.5 before pasteurization.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You'll get a boost by adding up to ten percent gypsum to the casing material.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>11663045</next>\n<prev>11662871</prev>\n<first>11662871</first>\n<last>11663046</last>\n<when>1261003090</when>\n<utime>12/17/09 12:38 AM</utime>\n</post>"}